<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><magicdraw><comment classType="Comment" humanType="Comment" icon="index_files/icon_comment_841774062.jpg" id="_16_8_246b03eb_1313142674517_976889_20159" refElementId="_16_8_246b03eb_1313142674517_976889_20159"><annotatedElement humanName="Annotated Element" mode="s,e"><class classType="Class" humanType="Class" icon="index_files/icon_class_555864569.jpg" name="RoleDefinition" refElementId="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830" refid="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830"/></annotatedElement><body humanName="Body" mode="s,e">A role definition defines a certain role in a system or application. Usually role definitions match with the definition of actors from the use case model. Roles are used to encapsulate authorization types which are assigned to a role for a period of time. This indirection is useful to ease the administration of privileges within a application. Instead of assigning lots of authorization types to a user account simply a role has to be assigned. </body><documentation humanName="Documentation"/><owner classType="Class" humanName="Owner" humanType="Class" icon="index_files/icon_class_555864569.jpg" mode="s,e" name="RoleDefinition" refElementId="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830" refid="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830"/><owningElement classType="Class" humanName="Owning Element" humanType="Class" icon="index_files/icon_class_555864569.jpg" name="RoleDefinition" refElementId="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830" refid="_16_0_1_2aa0154_1265061847640_355272_830"/><TO_DO humanName="To Do" mode="s,e"/></comment></magicdraw>